Sampling distribution

\[\text{Recall } \boldsymbol{X}_N = X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_N\]

\(\boldsymbol{X}_N\) is our notation for a series of measures from a sample of size \(N\).

Sampling distribution

If the measure of interest is \[X = \text{HbA1C,}\] then \[\boldsymbol{X}_{134}\] is HbA1C measurements from a sample of 134 individuals.

Sampling distribution

Weve been focused on a number of different transformations of the sample, \(\boldsymbol{X}_{N}\):

Transformation Formula
Mean \(\bar{X} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N X_i\)
Median \(X_{((N+1)/2)}\)
Variance \(s^2 = \frac{1}{N-1}\sum_{i=1}^N (X_i - \bar{X})^2\)
Min \(X_{(1)}\)
Max \(X_{(N)}\)

Sampling distribution

The sampling distribution is the distribution of the descriptive summaries from the sample.

\[\text{If } X_i\sim F_X(x), \text{ then } g(\boldsymbol{X}_N) \sim \text{Sampling distribution}\]

Example 1: Crazy mixture distribution

rf3 <- function(N){
  G <- sample(0:2, N, replace = TRUE, prob = c(5,3,2))
  (G==0)*rnorm(N) + (G==1)*rnorm(N,4) + (G==2)*rnorm(N,-4,2)
}

pf3 <- function(x){
  .5*pnorm(x) + .3*pnorm(x,4) + .2*pnorm(x,-4,2)
}

df3 <- function(x){
  .5*dnorm(x) + .3*dnorm(x,4) + .2*dnorm(x,-4,2)
}

Example 1: Crazy mixture distribution

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
curve(pf3(x), -10, 9, lwd = 3, col = "blue", ylab = "Probability")
curve(df3(x), -10, 9, lwd = 3, col = "darkgreen", ylab = "Density")

Sampling distribution of the variance via simulation

N <- 134
M <- 5000
X <- array(rf3(N*M), dim = c(M,N)) 
vars <- apply(X, 1, var)
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(ecdf(vars), main = "ECDF")
hist(
    vars
  , breaks = 50
  , main = "EPDF"
  , freq = FALSE
  , border = "white"
  , col = "gray50"
  , xlab = "x"
)
box()

Sampling distribution

If we know the underlying distribution of the data and we can sample from it, then we can use simulation to uncover the sampling distribution.

\[\text{If we can sample from } F_X(x), \text{ then we can uncover } g(\boldsymbol{X}_N)\]

Reality check: Usually \(F_X(x)\) is unknown.

Reality check: We only have a single sample, \(\boldsymbol{X}_N\)

Sampling distribution

Example: Glycohemoglobin from NHANES

id gh age sex
1 5.2 34.2 male
2 5.7 16.8 male
3 6 60.2 female
4 5.1 26.1 male
5 5.3 49.7 female

Sampling distribution from a single sample

To uncover the sampling distribution from a single sample, we are going to simulate from the sample. This tool is known as the bootstrap.

Bootstrap

Basic Idea: Create new samples of size \(N\) by sampling rows with replacement.

Bootstrap

Example: Glycohemoglobin from NHANES

id gh age sex
891 4.7 42.4 male
6222 6.7 60.9 female
615 5.8 65.7 male
615 5.8 65.7 male
6431 4.7 43.7 female

Boostrap

A new sample generated in this way is often called a bootstrap sample or bootstrap replicate.

Boostrap

A new sample generated in this way is often called a bootstrap sample or bootstrap replicate.

A summary measure can be calculated for each bootstrap sample, like the variance or the mean.

Boostrap

A new sample generated in this way is often called a bootstrap sample or bootstrap replicate.

A summary measure can be calculated for each bootstrap sample, like the variance or the mean.

The distribution of the summary measures calculated on bootstrap samples is called the bootstrap distribution.

Bootstrap

There are bootstrap specific tools in R. For discussion and demonstration purposes, we are going to bootstrap by “hand”.

Example: Bootstrap distribution of the variance of gh

Hmisc::getHdata(nhgh) #loads nhgh, the NHANES data
gh <- nhgh$gh
n_gh <- length(gh)
M <- 5000
out <- rep(NA, M)
for(i in 1:M){
  index <- sample.int(n_gh, n_gh, replace = TRUE)
  out[i] <- gh[index] %>% var
}

Bootstrap

Example: Bootstrap distribution of the variance of gh

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(ecdf(out), lwd = 3, main = "ECDF")
hist(
    out
  , main = "EPDF"
  , ylab = "Density"
  , xlab = "Bootstrap variances"
  , breaks = 50
  , freq = FALSE
  , border = "white"
  , col = "gray50"
)
box()
